  "text": "Block of I Cir,swell by Gd 3ϩ and the resulting volume changes were dose dependent. Normal cells first were swollen in 0.6T to activate I Cir,swell and then were exposed for 5-minute periods to successively higher doses of Gd 3ϩ (1 to 30 mol/L) in 0.6T solution. As the Gd 3ϩ concentration was progressively increased, the magnitude of the blocked current increased significantly ( Figure 7A ), and relative cell volume decreased significantly ( Figure 7B ). The dose dependence of the effects of Gd 3ϩ was also examined in CHF cells bathed in isosmotic solution, conditions under which I Cir,swell was already activated. As for normal cells, exposing CHF cells to successively higher Gd 3ϩ concentrations for 5-minute periods resulted in stepwise block of I Cir,swell ( Figure 7C ) and decrease of cell volume ( Figure 7D ). Dose-response curves for Gd 3ϩ -sensitive current at -80 mV and cell volume are shown in Figure 8A for normal cells and in Figure 8C for CHF cells. To compare the present results with each other and with previous work, 14 data from Figure 7 were fitted to the Hill equation, and the responses were plotted, with the fitted maximum taken as 1. The K 0. 5 and Hill coefficient for current and volume estimated from the fitted curves were 2.0Ϯ0.2 mol/L and 1.9Ϯ0.4 and 2.1Ϯ0.3 mol/L and 1.8Ϯ0.3, respectively, in normal cells and 2.0Ϯ0.2 mol/L and 1.9Ϯ0.4 and 1.9Ϯ0.2 mol/L and 2.0Ϯ0.3, respectively, in CHF cells. Cooperative binding and a sigmoidal dose-response relationship for Gd 3ϩ were reported previously. [CITATION_1] 26 To compare the responses of normal and CHF cells, a two-way ANOVA with factors cell type, dose, and cell typeϫdose was performed for Gd 3ϩ -induced block of current and cell shrinkage ( Figure 8A and 8C) . F-ratio tests on the interaction term indicated that the current (Pϭ0.725) and volume (Pϭ0.804) responses of normal and CHF cells were indistinguishable. Moreover, the fit parameters were similar to those obtained in rabbit myocytes.",
